    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-11T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-11T10:00:00-05:00" n="257"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/13879: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-11T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 11, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 12—9:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1476. Brigadier General Zigmund Bohusz, Chief of the Polish Military Mission in
                    Moscow, told me this afternoon: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>As the result of conferences with the Soviet authorities he believes
                            it will be possible to raise four or five divisions of Polish troops in
                            the Soviet Union, the first of which he desires to motorize.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>The British Government has expressed its willingness and ability to
                            outfit these four or five divisions with British uniforms and a limited
                            quantity of arms and munitions.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>The Polish Mission hopes to be able to obtain a limited amount of arms
                            and munitions from material taken by the Soviet Army at the time of the
                            invasion of Poland and to supplement these with the necessary additional
                            material from the United States.</item>
                        <label>(4)</label>
                        <item>The General stated that in his opinion these divisions would be ready
                            for action in 3 months provided they could be equipped and munitioned
                            within that time.</item>
                        <label>(5)</label>
                        <item>The Polish Government contemplates appointing either Kott,<note n="3"
                                xml:id="d257fn3">Stanislaw Kot was appointed as the Polish
                                Ambassador to the Soviet Union.</note> now Minister of Interior in
                            London, or Skolnitsky, former Polish <pb facs="0261" n="249"
                                xml:id="pg_249"/> Counselor in Helsinki and now in Stockholm, as
                            Polish Ambassador to the Soviet Union.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[Concerning the <hi rend="italic">ukaz</hi> of August 12, 1941, of the
                        Presidium of the Supreme Council of the Soviet Union which amnestied all
                        Polish citizens confined on Soviet territory as prisoners of war, or for
                        other sufficient reasons, see telegram No. 1488, August 13, 1941, from the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union, <ref target="#pg_638">page 638</ref>.]</p>
                </postscript>
